{"key":"processedPost-12361125","value":{"id":12361125,"first":12355534,"last":12362842,"when":1270830530,"utime":"04/09/10 07:28 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>myco.alchemist said:</b><br />If you don't buffer the peat ph.<br />You will FUTW's<br />Result is often no pinning, or pinning around the edges only.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Correct.<br /><br />You always buffer a peat casing mix.&nbsp; If you don't, it will be green before first flush.<br /><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>jingus said:</b><br />so i'm doing it 50%peat moss 50%vermiculite, i won't bother going into town for lime or gypsum.<br /><br />but my question is this.&nbsp;  i just watched RR's casing video again, where he hydrated the two separately, but i want to know if i can pasteurize my casing the same way i pasteurize my bulk.<br /><br />i'd like to mix the two in a 5 gallon bucket, add 165degree water, and let it sit for an hour or so,&nbsp; then strain it out through an old tapestry, and get it to field capacity by hand.&nbsp; (it works great for bulk, i swear)<br /><br />do you guys see a problem with this?&nbsp; i can't imagine it helps much to hydrate the peat moss and vermic separately.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Big problems.&nbsp; First, if it's too much trouble to go into town for lime and gypsum, you're in the wrong hobby.&nbsp; <br /><br />Second, you need to maintain the temperature in the center of the casing mix at 140F to 160F for one full hour.&nbsp; Pouring hot water over the material and letting it sit ain't gonna cut it.<br /><br />Third, peat and verm hydrate at different rates, so it's always best to moisten them separately and then mix.&nbsp; Taking shortcuts until you know all the ropes is asking for failure. The casing layer tek was produced after doing this a few thousand times.&nbsp; It wasn't designed to make you take unnecessary steps.<br />RR","title":"Re: pasteurizing a casing","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}